    "created_at": "2015-07-22T14:47:10Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-07-22T14:47:10Z",
    "body": "> The TaskDialog API removes the close button when the dialog has a parent window, I don't see a flag to bring it back.\n\nSo maybe it's influenced by the styles of the parent.\n\nAccording to Microsoft's [design guidelines](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/windows/desktop/dn742499%28v=vs.85%29.aspx) for dialog boxes in desktop apps, there should always be a close button on the title bar:\n\n> - Dialog boxes always have a Close button. Modeless dialogs can also have a Minimize button. Resizable dialogs can have a Maximize button.\n> - Don't disable the Close button. Having a Close button helps users stay in control by allowing them to close windows they don't want.\n>   - Exception: For progress dialogs, you may disable the Close button if the task must run to completion to achieve a valid state or prevent data loss.\n\nThey mention it again in:\n\n> For modeless dialogs, use an explicit Close command button in the dialog to close the window. For both, use a Close button on the title bar to close the window.\n\nThat said, I did a Google image search for TaskDialog and it seems that in practice not everyone follows the guidelines (about half of the dialogs don't have a close button on the title bar).\n\nThanks for the quick response :smile: \n"
  },
